For the better part of two years, my debugging strategy was a single line of code repeated with religious devotion. Something breaks, I sprinkle console.log("here 1"), console.log("here 2"), console.log("WHY", data) Across the file like seasoning, refresh the browser, squint at the output, and repeat. It worked. Mostly. It also cost me hours I will never get back, usually on a Friday evening, usually right before a client demo.

6 min read
5 hours ago

--

Press enter or click to view image in full size

I still use console.log. I am not writing this to tell you it is beneath you. But somewhere around my second year building on React and TypeScript, working on a data platform that pulls from a Frappe backend with its own opinions about how errors should surface, I realized that logging was a crutch I leaned on because I never learned the tools sitting right next to it. This is the story of how I stopped guessing and started actually watching my code run.
The bug that broke my console.log habit
We were building out a dynamic form component for a food fortification data platform I work on. Think of it as a form renderer that takes a schema and spits out the right Ant Design fields, dropdowns for some rows, date pickers for others, conditional fields that appear only when a previous answer matches a certain value. Standard stuff, until it wasn’t.
Users started reporting that certain fields would silently reset when they typed into an unrelated field elsewhere in the form. No error in the console. No red flag anywhere. Just data quietly vanishing.
My first instinct was the usual one. Log the form state before and after the keystroke. I did that for about forty minutes, staring at nested objects that looked identical between renders, convinced I was losing my mind. The bug wasn’t in the data. It was in when and why the component was re-rendering in the first place, and no amount of logging state was going to show me that. I needed to see the renders themselves, not just the values they carried.
That was the moment I opened React DevTools’ Profiler tab for a reason other than curiosity.
Watch how your components actually render
The Profiler tab records a session and shows you exactly which components rendered, how long each took, and, more importantly, why. Click record, reproduce the bug, stop recording, and you get a flame graph of your component tree colored by render cost.
In my case, it turned out an unrelated renderFields function was recreating a new object reference on every keystroke, which meant a child field component saw a "new" prop object even though the values were unchanged, which triggered a reset effect I had wired up carelessly with useEffect. No amount of console.log(props) would have shown me that the object was structurally identical but referentially new. The Profiler showed it to me in about four minutes.
If you have never turned this on, do it today. Right click any component in the Components tab, there is a small option to log it to the console as a variable, and suddenly you are inspecting live props and state the way you would inspect any object, not the way you would inspect a wall of text scrolling past in your terminal.
Breakpoints do more than pause your code
For a long time I thought breakpoints were just a fancier debugger statement, a place where execution stops so you can look around. That is true, but it undersells what they can do.
Conditional breakpoints changed how I debug loops and list renders. Instead of logging inside a .map() and scrolling through fifty identical lines to find the one broken row, you right click the line number in Chrome DevTools, add a condition like row.id === 'ferrous-sulfate-42', and execution only stops when that specific condition is true. You land exactly where the problem is, with the full call stack and every variable in scope, instead of reconstructing the moment from log fragments.
Logpoints are the quieter cousin of this feature. You right click a line, choose “Add logpoint” instead of a breakpoint, type an expression, and DevTools logs it to the console every time that line runs, without you touching the source file. No more forgetting to delete a stray console.log before pushing a commit. No more that awkward moment in a pull request review where someone gently points out you left console.log("delete me") in a utility function that made it past your linter somehow. I have done this. More than once.
// instead of this, scattered through your source
console.log('field value changed', fieldId, newValue);// set a logpoint on the relevant line in DevTools:
// `field value changed`, fieldId, newValue
// same output, zero commits, zero cleanupStop guessing what the network is doing
Frontend bugs love to hide at the boundary between your code and the backend, and if you are working against something like a Frappe or ERPNext API, that boundary has its own personality. I have chased phantom bugs that turned out to be a password validation error thrown from a Python function with a signature mismatch, or a MySQL column error that had nothing to do with the component I was staring at.
The Network tab in DevTools is where these mysteries get solved, but most people only use it to check status codes. The better habit is opening the response payload directly and reading what the backend actually says, not what your error boundary decided to show the user. A generic “Something went wrong” toast in your UI is often hiding a very specific, very useful error message sitting one click away in the response body.
I got into the habit of pairing this with the “Preserve log” checkbox, especially for bugs involving redirects or page reloads, since without it your evidence disappears the moment the page refreshes. I also started filtering by Fetch/XHR and using the initiator column to trace exactly which function triggered a given call, which matters a lot more than it sounds once you are debugging a form with six different submission handlers wired to slightly different endpoints.
Read the stack trace like it’s trying to help you
Early on, I treated stack traces as noise to scroll past on the way to the actual error message. That was backwards. The stack trace is usually the most information-dense part of the whole error.
Wrapping a suspicious part of your tree in an error boundary and actually reading the componentStack it gives you, rather than just catching the error and showing a fallback UI, tells you the exact path the render took to get there. Combined with source maps enabled in your build, even a minified production error becomes traceable back to the actual line in your TypeScript source, not some mangled bundle reference that means nothing to you.
class DebugBoundary extends React.Component<Props, State> {
state = { hasError: false };static getDerivedStateFromError() {
return { hasError: true };
}
componentDidCatch(error: Error, info: React.ErrorInfo) {
console.error('Component stack:', info.componentStack);
console.error('Error:', error);
}
render() {
if (this.state.hasError) return this.props.fallback;
return this.props.children;
}
}I wrapped one of these around a report listing component that was rendering thousands of rows in batches on scroll, and the component stack told me in one glance that a filter function was running before the data had finished normalizing, something I had been trying to reproduce manually for the better part of an afternoon.
Build yourself a debug toggle
The single change that saved me the most cumulative time was embarrassingly simple. I stopped ripping out debug logs when I was done with a feature and instead gated them behind a flag.
const DEBUG = localStorage.getItem('debug:forms') === 'true';export const debugLog = (...args: unknown[]) => {
if (DEBUG) console.log('[forms]', ...args);
};Now, when a bug resurfaces three weeks later in a part of the app I thought was finished, I do not start from zero. I flip localStorage.setItem('debug:forms', 'true') in the console, reload, and the trail of breadcrumbs I left myself is already there, clearly labeled, not mixed in with every other console statement in the app. It costs nothing in production since the flag defaults to off, and it turns future me into someone who is genuinely grateful for past me's paranoia.
What actually changed
None of these tools are exotic. They ship with every browser and every React install you already have. What changed for me was not the tooling, it was the willingness to spend fifteen minutes learning a feature instead of forty minutes brute forcing a workaround I already knew.
The next time something breaks and your first instinct is to reach for console.log, try pausing for a second. Ask whether you actually need to see a value, or whether you need to see a render, a network call, or a call stack instead. Pick the tool that answers the real question, and the fifteen minutes you spend learning it once will keep paying you back long after the bug is gone.
